text.tspan: Work in the Vicinity of an Entrance Ramp
1. An acceleration lane of suffcient length should be provided whenever possible as shown on the diagram
For the information shown on the diagram on the right-hand side of the typical application, where
inadequate acceleration distance exists for the temporary entrance, the YIELD sign shall be
replaced with STOP signs (one on each side of the approach).
3. When used, the YIELD or STOP sign should be located so that ramp vehicular traffc has adequate sight
distance of oncoming mainline vehicular traffc to select an acceptable gap in the mainline vehicular
traffc fow, but should not be located so far forward that motorists will be encouraged to stop in the path
of the mainline traffc. Also, a longer acceleration lane should be provided beyond the sign to reduce the
gap size needed. If suffcient gaps are not available, consideration should be given to closing the ramp.
4. Where a STOP sign is used, a temporary stop line should be placed across the ramp at the desired
5. The mainline merging taper with the arrow board at its starting point should be located suffciently
in advance so that the arrow board is not confusing to drivers on the entrance ramp, and so that
the mainline merging vehicular traffc from the lane closure has the opportunity to stabilize before
encountering the vehicular traffc merging from the ramp.
6. If the ramp curves sharply to the right, warning signs with advisory speeds located in advance of the
entrance terminal should be placed in pairs (one on each side of the ramp).
7. Positive protection devices may be used per Section 6M.02.
A Stop Beacon (see Section 4S.05) or a Type B high-intensity warning fasher with a red lens may be
9. Where the acceleration distance is signifcantly reduced, a supplemental plaque may be placed below the
Yield Ahead sign reading NO MERGE AREA.
10. An arrow board shall be used when a freeway lane is closed. When more than one freeway lane is
closed, a separate arrow board shall be used for each closed lane.
